50 miles off the Florida coast on Monday,Navy ships rammed and fire-hosed the 190-foot MV Greenpeace vesselwhile helicopters buzzed two small high-speed rafts. Sailors inmotorized rafts cut the fuel lines of one Greenpeace raft beforetowing both out of the launch safety zone.   With their vessels helpless, about 25 Greenpeace activists couldonly watch as the nuclear submarine Tennessee unleashed the Trident2, the Navy's newest, most powerful weapon, on a successful testlaunch.   The 44-foot missile shot out of a tube in the sub's deck, brokethe sea's surface, ignited and hurled a dummy warhead package to anocean target several thousand miles away.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Bush administration is scrambling toreplace M. Danny Wall, who is resigning as the nation's top savingsand loan regulator after 2{ years of bitter struggle with Congress.   Wall, characterizing his job as a ``thankless and perhapsimpossible task,'' resigned in a letter to President Bush onMonday. He said he was leaving to spare his Office of ThriftSupervision the disruption that would be caused by continuing hisfight for political survival.   Until Thanksgiving, the House Banking Committee was holdingweekly hearings spotlighting Wall's failure to contain what couldbecome the nation's largest Sandamp;L failure. The regulator was spendingmuch of his time responding to his critics.   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady praised Wall for his``public spirited'' decision to resign and said the department hadbegan the search for his successor.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Justice Department is conducting apreliminary inquiry on whether a special prosecutor shouldinvestigate allegations that former Housing Secretary Samuel R.Pierce violated the law.   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh disclosed late Monday that hehad ordered the preliminary inquiry into allegations submitted lastmonth by 19 Democrats on the House Judiciary Committee.   The department has 60 days to complete the preliminary inquiry.Thornburgh's chief spokesman David Runkel said it began Saturday.   Under the law, the inquiry by the Justice Department's publicintegrity section must determine if there are ``reasonable groundsto believe that further investigation is warranted'' by specialprosecutor, known as an independent counsel.</TEXT></DOC>